# TTS Audio Generation

## Quick Start

Generate audio for a lesson:
```bash
npm run tts:generate -- --lesson 04 --model gemini
```

## Model Strategy: Flash for Words, Pro for Sentences

Two Gemini TTS models are used depending on content type:

### gemini-2.5-flash-tts (single words / short phrases)
- **Use for:** Vocabulary (`words/`), grammar table rows (`grammar/`), grammar table notes
- **Prompt:** `"make sure the word is clearly in Bulgarian with the right pronunciation"`
- **Why:** Better pronunciation accuracy for isolated words

### gemini-2.5-pro-tts (connected text)
- **Use for:** Dialogues, reading texts, listening, grammar examples (full sentences), personal choice models, **illustrated_cards** (greeting phrases like „Добър ден!“ — natural stress/intonation)
- **Prompt:** `"Read aloud in a warm, welcoming tone."`
- **Why:** More natural intonation and flow for sentences and paragraphs

### Override: `GRAMMAR_TABLE_PRO_ROWS`
Some grammar table rows need Pro instead of Flash (e.g. multi-syllable numbers like "хиляда"). Add the row key to this `Set` in `generate-tts.ts`.

### Common settings
- **API:** Google Cloud TTS via OAuth (`texttospeech.googleapis.com/v1/text:synthesize`)
- **Auth:** Service account (`service-account.json` in project root, gitignored)
- **Output:** MP3
- **Rate limit:** ~10 req/min → script uses 6.5s delay between requests
- **Voices:**
  - `Achernar` — female (default)
  - `Despina` — second female (when two women alternate in dialogues)
  - `Charon` — male
  - `Achird` — second male (when two men alternate in dialogues)

### Why Gemini over Chirp3-HD

Chirp3-HD (`bg-BG-Chirp3-HD-*`) has accent/stress issues on Bulgarian words. Gemini TTS produces more natural pronunciation with correct stress patterns.

## Fallback Model: Chirp3-HD

```bash
npm run tts:generate -- --lesson 05 --model chirp
```
- Uses API key (`GOOGLE_TTS_API_KEY` in `.env.local`)
- Voices: `bg-BG-Chirp3-HD-Achernar`, `bg-BG-Chirp3-HD-Charon`
- Speaking rate: 0.85
- Rate limit: 10 req/s

## File Structure

```
public/assets/lesson-XX/audio/tts/
  words/         — {vocabularyItemId}.mp3
  dialogues/     — {exerciseId}-{sectionId}-line-{index}.mp3
  grammar/       — {exerciseId}-row-{index}.mp3  (tables)
                   {exerciseId}-card-{index}.mp3  (examples)
                   {exerciseId}-note-{index}.mp3  (table notes)
  texts/         — {exerciseId}-p-{index}.mp3     (per paragraph)
                   {exerciseId}-full.mp3           (full text, <2000 chars)
                   {exerciseId}-model.mp3          (personal_choice model)
  listening/     — {exerciseId}.mp3
```

## What Gets Generated

| Category | Source | Voice | Model |
|---|---|---|---|
| Vocabulary | `content.vocabulary[].bulgarian` | Female | Flash |
| Illustrated cards | `exercises[type=illustrated_cards].cards[]` — **`label` only**; set `ttsIncludeSublabels: true` to join sublabels into one clip | Female (Achernar) | **Pro** (`Read aloud in a warm, welcoming tone.`) — better intonation on short phrases than Flash |
| Image labeling | `words/{image.id}.mp3` for images **not** covered by an illustrated card with the same `id` (e.g. a flag-only country) | Female | Flash |
| Dialogues | `exercises[type=dialogues].sections[].lines[]` | Per speaker | Pro |
| Grammar tables | `exercises[type=grammar_table].rows[]` | Female | Flash (or Pro via override) |
| Grammar table notes | `exercises[type=grammar_table].notes[]` | Female | Flash |
| Grammar visual (pronouns) | `exercises[type=grammar_visual].pronouns[]` | Female | Flash (`{exerciseId}-pronoun-{i}.mp3`) |
| Grammar examples | `exercises[type=grammar_examples].examples[]` | Female by default; set `voiceGender: 'male'` on a card for Charon (e.g. lines spoken by a male character) | Pro |
| Reading texts | `exercises[type=reading_text].paragraphs[]` | Female by default; `voiceGender` on exercise for all paragraphs; or `paragraphVoiceGenders[]` (same length as `paragraphs`) for per-paragraph voice — then **no** `-full.mp3`; UI uses sequential „Слушай“ | Pro |
| Listening | `exercises[].listeningText` | Female | Pro |
| Personal choice models | `exercises[type=personal_choice].model` | Female | Pro |

## What Does NOT Get Generated

- Interactive exercises (fill_blank, dropdown, drag, etc.)
- Cards with `disableTts: true`
- Exercises in per-lesson exclude lists (e.g., workbook exercises)

## Speaker Voice Map (Dialogues)

| Speaker | Voice |
|---|---|
| Клиент | Female (Achernar) |
| Продавач | Male (Charon) |
| Fallback | Alternating by line index (even=female, odd=male) |

### Explicit `voiceGender` on dialogue lines (recommended)

In `exercises.ts`, each dialogue line may set `voiceGender: 'male' | 'female'` (TTS only; not shown in the UI). When set, it overrides the fallback alternation so a **male** line always uses a male voice.

**Two men in a row:** the script alternates **`Charon`** and **`Achird`** (Gemini TTS). Chirp mode has only one Bulgarian male preset, so both map to Chirp Charon.

**Two women in a row:** the script alternates **`Achernar`** and **`Despina`** (Gemini TTS).

When adding new lessons with different speakers, update `SPEAKER_VOICE_MAP` in [generate-tts.ts](mdc:scripts/generate-tts.ts) and/or add `voiceGender` on lines where roles are clear.

### Playback in the UI
The [Dialogues.tsx](mdc:src/components/exercises/Dialogues.tsx) component gives every dialogue exercise **two** controls for free:
- **Per-line click** — plays a single MP3.
- **Per-section "Слушай / Listen" button** — plays all lines in the section back-to-back with a 350 ms gap (red "Спри / Stop" while active).

Both modes rely on the same `dialogues/{exerciseId}-{sectionId}-line-{i}.mp3` files, so just running `npm run tts:generate -- --lesson XX --model gemini` is enough — no extra audio assets needed. See also the `exercise-ui` rule.

## Text Cleaning

Two cleaning functions exist:
- **`cleanForGeminiTTS()`** (Gemini): Light touch — strips leading dashes, removes parenthetical labels
- **`cleanForTTS()`** (Chirp): Aggressive — converts slashes/dashes to commas, removes exclamation marks, strips parentheses

## Content Rules for TTS Quality

These rules in **content files** directly affect audio quality:
- **Numbers as words** in `listeningText` and `reading_text.paragraphs` — write „седемдесет и шест" not „76". TTS reads digits unnaturally.
- **Period, not dash** between sums — `'Рестото. Четири евро.'` not `'Рестото — четири евро.'`. Dashes confuse pacing.
- **No markdown** in text fields — TTS reads asterisks, brackets etc. Keep text clean.
- **voiceGender on every dialogue line** where the speaker's gender is clear (male/female). Fallback alternation works but explicit is better.
- **Problematic words** — add to `GRAMMAR_TABLE_PRO_ROWS` if a Flash-generated word sounds wrong. Examples: „хиляда", „милиард", „вие работите".

## Audio Files in Git — IMPORTANT, READ BEFORE TOUCHING `.gitattributes`

### The rule (non-negotiable)

**MP3 files are committed as regular Git blobs. NOT Git LFS.**

### Why (so nobody "fixes" this again)

Vercel's build process does **not** run `git lfs fetch` by default. If MP3s are tracked by LFS, the deployed site serves LFS pointer text files instead of real audio → every „Слушай" button plays a broken file. We hit this bug already and rolled back. Total MP3 size is ~30 MB — this is fine in regular Git and does not justify LFS.

### What `.gitattributes` must look like

```gitattributes
# *.mp3 is NOT listed here — on purpose
*.wav filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
*.ogg filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
```

- `*.mp3` → **must NOT** appear with `filter=lfs`
- `*.wav` and `*.ogg` stay in LFS (source/intermediate files, not shipped to prod)

### How to commit TTS output (the only correct flow)

```bash
npm run tts:generate -- --lesson XX --model gemini
git add -A
git commit -m "feat(lesson-XX): TTS audio"
git push
```

No `git lfs track`, no `git lfs migrate`, no special commands. Just plain git.

### Do NOT do any of these

- ❌ Do **not** run `git lfs track "*.mp3"`
- ❌ Do **not** add `*.mp3 filter=lfs …` to `.gitattributes`
- ❌ Do **not** run `git lfs migrate import --include="*.mp3"`
- ❌ Do **not** rename/move MP3 files manually — paths are derived by `getTtsAudioPath()` from exercise/vocabulary IDs

### Sanity check before pushing audio — ALWAYS RUN THIS

```bash
npm run check:audio
```

Expected output:
```
✓ .gitattributes does not route *.mp3 through LFS
✓ All N tracked *.mp3 files are real binaries (no LFS pointers)
```

If it fails, the script prints exactly how to fix it. Do NOT push until it passes.

**Automatic protection:** `npm run build` (and therefore every Vercel deploy)
runs `check:audio` as `prebuild`. A broken MP3 will fail the build instead of
shipping a silent site.

### If `check:audio` reports LFS pointers

This happens when MP3 blobs in git history are still pointer files (typically
from an earlier LFS experiment). Fix:

```bash
git add --renormalize -- "public/assets/**/*.mp3"
git commit -m "fix(audio): renormalize MP3s out of LFS"
git push
npm run check:audio   # must now pass
```

## Adding a New Lesson — Checklist

1. Ensure `content.ts` and `exercises.ts` are complete for the lesson
2. Check for special cases: `voiceGender: 'male'` on exercises, `disableTts: true` on cards
3. Add any lesson-specific excludes to `READING_TEXT_EXCLUDE` or `SKIP_FULL_TEXT` in generate-tts.ts
4. If dialogues have new speaker roles, add them to `SPEAKER_VOICE_MAP`
5. Run: `npm run tts:generate -- --lesson XX --model gemini`
6. Script skips existing files — safe to re-run after fixing issues
7. To regenerate specific files, delete them first, then re-run
8. Verify in browser: `npm run dev` → navigate to lesson
9. Run `npm run check:audio` — **must** print `✓ All N tracked *.mp3 files are real binaries`. If it fails, see **Audio Files in Git** above.
10. Commit and push: `git add -A` → `git commit` → `git push`. MP3 files are plain Git blobs — no LFS commands needed.

## Convention-Based Audio Paths

Components use `getTtsAudioPath()` from [src/lib/tts.ts](mdc:src/lib/tts.ts) to construct paths by convention:
```
/assets/lesson-{num}/audio/tts/{category}/{filename}.mp3
```
No manual `audioUrl` needed for vocabulary, dialogues, or grammar — the path is derived from exercise ID. Reading texts use `audioUrl` in exercises.ts pointing to the `-full.mp3` file.

